1.1. Why Java?

Java White Paper:

  • Simple, Object-Oriented and Familiar
  • Robust & secure
  • Architecture neutral and portable
  • High performance
  • Interpreted, threaded, and dynamic

Faster development cycle, less compiling and shite
Constant garbage collection for good memory management
Multithreading is basked into Java programs
Maintains the OOP nature of C++ but more secure, robust, convenient

Contrast with Traditional Software Development

C/C++ is compiled to 'native code' which cannot be ported between machines
Java executable (.jar) runs on any machine via a virtual machine
Java compiles to 'bytecode' (.jar file)
Java is highly employable

1.2. Getting started with Java

Download and install the latest Java SDK. Easiest to use the installer.
Download and install IntelliJ (IDE)

1.3. Hello World

/*
Multiline comments like this
@author Thomas O'Dea
@version 1.0 09-09-2024
Those lines are 'JavaDoc' notation
*/
public class HelloWorld {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello, World"); // Print
    }
}
  • First we declare a class (everything needs a class)
  • Then declare a method
    - Our main method gets String[] args from CLI
  • Then instructions, semicolon delimited
    - 'system' is a built-in class of Java

There should be one class in a source (text) file, and the file should have the same name with .java (HelloWorld.java) always capitalised

1.4. Data Types

Java will automatically cast an int to a String if passed into a String argument
e.g. "Your balance is " + balance + " euros".
Integers:

  • int (4 bytes)
  • short (2 bytes)
  • long (8 bytes)
  • byte (1 byte)

Also:

  • char
  • double
  • boolean

Variables can be inferred implicitly, e.g.
var stage = 1;
Constants are declared with the 'final' keyword. Convention is that their names be all uppercase with underscores.

enum types are useful:


enum Grade {A, B, C, D, FAIL};

Grade studentGrade = Grade.B;

System.out.println("Your grade is "+studentGrade)

// Implicit string casting will take the enumerated name here! cool

1.5. Operators

The 'math' class contains useful methods for arithmetic (e.g. Math.sqrt(x))

Doubles can be cast to int e.g.

double ySqrt = Math.sqrt(y);
int ySqrtInt = (int) ySqrt;

Behaviour is truncation

Standard incrementors i++; i--; ++i; --i;

Ternary operator: condition ? iftrue ? else

if A and B uses short-circuit logic

1.7. I/O

User input

Need to import 'Scanner' package

import java.util.Scanner;
// you can also just import all of util with import java.util.*;

Create a scanner object and use it:

Scanner in = new Scanner(System.in);
String rawInput = in.nextLine();
String rawNumberInput = in.nextInt();

Formatting Numbers

import java.util.*;

public class FormattedNumber {
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		double numberIncorrectCast = 100/3;
		// This calculates as integers, then casts, so you get 33.0
		double numberCorrectCast = 100.0/3.0;
		// This is correct
		System.out.printf("Compare %8.2f %8.2f\n", numberIncorrectCast, numberCorrectCast);
		
		String name = "Thomas";
		char letter = 'j';
		boolean fact = true;
		int age = 18;
		System.out.printf("Details: %s %c %b %d\n", name, letter, fact, age);
	}
}

File I/O

import java.util.*;
import java.io.*;

public class CopyFile {
	public static  void main(String[] args) throws FileNotFoundException {
		// Create i/o objects for each file
		Scanner in = new Scanner(new File("fileInput.txt"));
		PrintWriter out = new PrintWriter("fileOutput.txt");
		String inputData;
		while (in.hasNextLine()) {
		// ^ this prevents it reading beyond the file's end
			inputData = in.nextLine();
			out.println(inputData);
		}
		// files must be closed
		in.close();
		out.close();
	}
}

1.8. Control Flow

do {
	anything();
} while(condition);

while (condition) {
	doSomething();
}

if (condition) {
	doThings();
} else {
	doOtherThings();
}

if (condition) doThings(); else doOtherThings();

switch (x) {
	case 0,1 -> doSomething();
	case 2,3 -> doAnotherThing();
	default -> finalOption();
}

int dayNumber = switch(dayName) {
	case "MONDAY"    -> 1;
	case "TUESDAY"   -> 2;
	// etc.
}

Labelled Breaks

main_loop:
for (int i=0; i<10; i++) {
	for (int j=0; j<3; j++) {
		if (i>3) 
			break main_loop;
		// 'break' can take a label to search for
	}
}
// will continue here after breaking!```

  • Static methods can be accessed without creating an instance
  • Use getter and setter methods, never interface directly with the fields - make fields private and getter/setter methods public

Packages

  • Packages organise class libraries

  • Declare what package your class is in at the beginning of the file:

    package com.hortsmann.corejava;
import java.time.*;
public class Employee {
	// more code here
}

  • Then import as a package in another

    import com.hortsmann.corejava.Employee;

  • By convention package names are globally unique, so dev's prefix package names with their website address

JAR Files

Java Archive File

  • Allow bundling of many files
    • Source code, compiled classes, metadata, executable text, images, etc.
  • Advantages:
    • Security (they can be digitally signed)
    • Faster download, compressed
    • Portable
  • Standard means of distributing Java app

Creating JAR files
jar cfve jar-file entry-point-classname class-files

  • 'c': create
  • 'f': file output
  • 'v': verbose
  • 'e': create manifest

Executing JAR files
Extraction not necessary
java -jar jar-file

Extracting JAR files
jar xf jar-file

  • 'x': extract
  • 'f': file input

cd javadoc
javadoc -d doc *.java
cd ./doc/index-all.html

ArrayLists

Similar to arrays but can change size during runtime
Only usable for objects, not primitives

Autoboxing

  • All primitive types have class equivalents
    • e.g. 'Integer' for 'int'
  • This allows you to store primitives in an ArrayList via the wrapper

Java Inheritance

  • Concepts
  • Example: managers and employees
  • Polymorphism
  • Methods with variable number of parameters
  • Abstract classes
  • Enumeration classes
  • Pop quiz

Concepts

  • A class can inherit attributes from a 'parent' class
Example

Every employee in your company has a salary, DOB, and PPSN. You might create an 'employee' class to store those.

Only managers get 'bonuses' so you might create a Manager class, which inherits from Employee, and adds a 'bonus' attribute.

public class Manager extends Employee {
	private double bonus;
	
	Manager(String name, double salary, int year) {
		super(name, salary, year); // Call the super class constructor!
		bonus = 0;
	}
	
	public double getSalary() {
		double baseSalary = super.getSalary();
		return baseSalary + bonus;
	}
	
	public void setBonus(double b) {
		bonus = b;
	}
}

You can treat child classes as an instance of the parent class, e.g.

var staff = new Employee[3];
staff[0] = new Manager("Thomas O'Dea",80000,2000);
staff[0].setBonus(1000);

Polymorphism

Code can be written that will run on objects of various different classes.

In the above example, calling getSalary() will call the Manager function, even if the array stores Employee objects.

See more at w3schools.

Preventing Inheritance

  • A 'final' class cannot have subclasses
public final class Executive extends Manager {...}
  • A final method cannot be overridden
public final String getName() {...}

Casting an Object

You can cast an inherited object into an instance of the parent object

If you do, you can later cast back and it will retain values it had from the subclass before.

Methods with Variable Number of Paramters

package multipleparameters;

public class Max{
	public static void main (String[] args) {
		double largest = max(1.0, 0.5, 1.5);
	}

	private static double max (double... values) {
		double largest = Double.NEGATIVE_INFINITY;
		for (double v : values ) {
			if (v > largest) {
				largest = v;
			}
		}
		return largest;
	}
}

Abstract Classes

Abstract classes cannot be instantiated as an object, they only exist to inherit more classes from

Abstract methods are simply placeholders for methods that will be overwritten in the inheriting class.

Example
  • UCD has to track professors and students.
  • Create a 'person' class. Because everybody will either fall under 'professor' or 'student' class, 'person' should be an abstract class.
public abstract class Person {
	public abstract String getDescription();
	
	private String name;
	
	public Person(String name) {
		this.name = name;
	}
	
	public String getName() {
		return name;
	}
}

public class Student extends Person {
	private String major;
	
	public Student(String name, String major) {
		super(name);
		// we can only use the abstract class because we have extended it
		this.major = major;
	}
	
	// Overwrite the abstract method
	public String getDescription() {
		return "a student majoring in "+major;
	}
}

This is generally used for security purposes.

Enumeration Classes

Enumeration actually creates a class

public enum Size {SMALL, MEDIUM, LARGE, EXTRA_LARGE}

All enumerated types extend the abstract class Enum. They inherit methods:

  • toString() - returns name of the value as string
  • toValue() - converts string to enum'd value
  • values() - returns an array of all the enum'd elements
  • ordinal() - returns the position of the enum'd value in the original enum declaration
Example

You can add your own methods to an 'enum' class

enum Size {
	SMALL("S"), MEDIUM("M"), LARGE("L"), EXTRA_LARGE("XL");
	
	private String abbreviation;

	Size (STring abbreviation) {
		this.abbreviation = abbreviation;
	}
	public String getAbbreviation() {
		return abbreviation;
	}
}
